From 1409981deca9507b2c0f9e2bfd761b737f7df3de Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: "Claude (T08-F9)" <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Mon, 27 Apr 2026 17:30:16 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] fix(cron): explicit timeout_milliseconds + parallelise org
 loop (T08-F9)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Why: net.http_post() defaults timeout_milliseconds to 5000ms in
pg_net 0.19.5. send-lesson-reminders takes ~5s end-to-end on 49 orgs
Г— 0 lessons (the steady state) because the outer org loop is sequential
and each org issues a 4-deep join lessons query. pg_net abandons the
HTTP request at 5000ms and writes a "Timeout of 5000 ms reached" row to
net._http_response on every cron fire. The edge function itself
completes correctly on Supabase's separate 60s wall clock вЂ” the work
gets done вЂ” but observability is structurally broken because every
firing looks like a timeout.

What: (1) New migration re-registers all 16 HTTP cron wrappers with an
explicit timeout_milliseconds := 60000, matching the edge function wall
clock. (2) Outer org loop in send-lesson-reminders/index.ts now uses
the runChunked helper introduced by T08-F6, with ORG_CONCURRENCY = 5.
Per-org error isolation is preserved by collapsing the existing
try/catch into the iteratee body. (3) docs/CRON_AUTH.md template
brought up to date (T08-P2-C1 wrapper shape + F9 timeout). (4)
docs/CRON_HEALTH.md severity table replaces the abandoned
registration-window-suppression row with the actual C4 condition.

Out of scope: T08-F8 (pg_cron return_message correlation) вЂ” pg_cron
1.6.4 writes the command tag "1 row" instead of the SELECT result, so
the watchdog's request_id-based join remains broken until F8 introduces
a request log table. F9 restores real status_code rows in
net._http_response, which is necessary but not sufficient for Class B.

Track 0.8 follow-up. Closes the symptom that motivated T08-F6 (which
remains correct as the inner-fan-out improvement).
