+-- T08-F9: Add explicit timeout_milliseconds := 60000 to all 16 cron HTTP
+-- wrappers.
+--
+-- Background: net.http_post(...) defaults timeout_milliseconds to 5000
+-- (verified 2026-04-27 against pg_net 0.19.5 on production via
+-- pg_proc inspection). The send-lesson-reminders edge function takes
+-- ~5s to process 49 orgs and is right on the ceiling, producing a
+-- "Timeout of 5000 ms reached" row in net._http_response on every fire
+-- even though the edge function itself completes correctly on
+-- Supabase's separate 60s wall clock.
+--
+-- This migration re-registers all 16 HTTP crons with an explicit
+-- timeout (60000 ms), matching Supabase's edge function wall clock
+-- budget. The unschedule-then-schedule pattern is idempotent and safe
+-- to re-apply.
+--
+-- Two SQL-only crons (complete-expired-assignments,
+-- reset-stale-practice-streaks) have no HTTP layer and are
+-- intentionally untouched, matching the T08-P2-C1 scope decision.
+--
+-- After this migration applies, every cron firing whose edge function
+-- returns within 60s will have a real status_code in net._http_response,
+-- restoring the observability premise of Track 0.8 Class B detection.
+-- (Note: the request_id correlation join is still broken вЂ” pg_cron 1.6.4
+-- writes the command tag "1 row" to job_run_details.return_message
+-- instead of the SELECT result. That is filed separately as T08-F8 and
+-- is out of scope for F9.)
